<subSubSection pageNumber="297" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="297">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="297">Note:</emphasis>
Although Fawcett &amp; Rendle (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="297">Fl. Jamaica</emphasis>
3: 197. 1914) and later authors including Keraudren-Aymonin (in Bosser &amp; al., 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="297">Fl. Mascareignes</emphasis>
34: 2. 1980) treated material in Herb. Sloane as type, this would not have been seen by Linnaeus and is not original material for the name. Le Thomas (in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Aubréville">Aubreville</normalizedToken>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="297">Fl. Gabon</emphasis>
16: 325. 1969) indicated unspecified material in LINN as the type but the only sheet there associated with this name (708.6) lacks the relevant 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="297">
<volumeTitle>Species Plantarum</volumeTitle>
</emphasis>
number (i.e. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“3”">&quot;3&quot;</normalizedToken>
) and was a post-1753 addition to the herbarium, and is also not original material for the name. Smith (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="297">Fl. Vitiensis Nova</emphasis>
2: 40. 1981) suggested that the cited Sloane plate would perhaps be the most suitable choice of type and this is now formalised here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
